They have lungs so well developed that they can leave the water and breathe in air. In Australia they are called salmon and baramunda. See Dipnoi, and Archipterygium

ceratohyal.definition: Pertaining to the bone, or cartilage, below the epihyal in the hyoid arch

ceratophyllaceae.definition: a natural family coextensive with the genus Ceratophyllum; the hornworts

ceratophyllum.definition: the sole genus constituting the family Ceratophyllaceae; the hornworts

ceratopogon.definition: the type genus of the Ceratopogonidae

ceratopogonidae.definition: a natural family of insects including the biting midges and sand flies

ceratopsia.definition: a suborder of extinct animals including triceratops

ceratopsian.definition: any of several four-footed herbivorous horned dinosaurs with enormous beaked skulls, of the late Cretaceous in North America and Mongolia

ceratopsidae.definition: an extinct family of American ceratopsian dinosaurs

ceratosaurus.definition: A swift-running bipedal carnivorous American Jurassic dinosaur allied to the European Megalosaurus. The animal was nearly twenty feet in length, and the skull bears a bony short horn between the nostrils on the united nasal bones. See Illustration in Appendix

ceratospongiae.definition: An order of sponges in which the skeleton consists of horny fibers. It includes all the commercial sponges

ceratozamia.definition: a small cycad of the genus Ceratozamia having a short scaly woody trunk and fernlike foliage and woody cones; Mexico

ceraunics.definition: That branch of physics which treats of heat and electricity

ceraunoscope.definition: An instrument or apparatus employed in the ancient mysteries to imitate thunder and lightning

cerberean.definition: Of or pertaining to, or resembling, Cerberus

cerberus.definition: A monster, in the shape of a three-headed dog, guarding the entrance into the infernal regions, Hence: Any vigilant custodian or guardian, esp. if surly
A genus of East Indian serpents, allied to the pythons; the bokadam

cercal.definition: Of or pertaining to the tail

cercaria.definition: The larval form of a trematode worm having the shape of a tadpole, with its body terminated by a tail-like appendage

cercarian.definition: Of, like, or pertaining to, the Cercariæ

cercopidae.definition: a natural family comprising the froghoppers or spittlebugs

cercopithecidae.definition: a natural family of Old World monkeys including the guenon, baboon, colobus monkey, langur, macaque, mandrill, mangabey, patas, and proboscis monkey

cercopithecus.definition: type genus of the Cercopithecidae, consisting of one genus of guenons

cercopod.definition: One of the jointed antenniform appendages of the posterior somites of certain insects

cercospora.definition: form genus of imperfect fungi that are leaf parasites with long slender spores

cercosporella.definition: form genus of imperfect fungi lacking pigment in the spores and conidiophores

cere.definition: The soft naked sheath at the base of the beak of birds of prey, parrots, and some other birds. See Beak
To wax; to cover or close with wax

cereal.definition: Of or pertaining to the grasses which are cultivated for their edible seeds (as wheat, maize, rice, etc.), or to their seeds or grain
Any grass cultivated for its edible grain, or the grain itself; -- usually in the plural

cerealia.definition: Public festivals in honor of Ceres

cerealin.definition: A nitrogenous substance closely resembling diastase, obtained from bran, and possessing the power of converting starch into dextrin, sugar, and lactic acid

cerebellar.definition: of or pertaining to the cerebellum; as, the cerebellar artery

cerebellum.definition: The large lobe of the hind brain in front of and above the medulla; the little brain. It controls combined muscular action. See Brain

cerebral.definition: Of or pertaining to the cerebrum
One of a class of lingual consonants in the East Indian languages. See Lingual, n

cerebralism.definition: The doctrine or theory that psychical phenomena are functions or products of the brain only

cerebrate.definition: To exhibit mental activity; to have the brain in action

cerebration.definition: Action of the brain, whether conscious or unconscious

cerebric.definition: Of, pertaining to, or derived from, the brain

cerebriform.definition: Like the brain in form or substance

cerebrifugal.definition: Applied to those nerve fibers which go from the brain to the spinal cord, and so transfer cerebral impulses (centrifugal impressions) outwards

cerebrin.definition: A nonphosphorized, nitrogenous substance, obtained from brain and nerve tissue by extraction with boiling alcohol. It is uncertain whether it exists as such in nerve tissue, or is a product of the decomposition of some more complex substance

cerebripetal.definition: Applied to those nerve fibers which go from the spinal cord to the brain and so transfer sensations (centripetal impressions) from the exterior inwards

cerebro-spinal.definition: Of or pertaining to the central nervous system consisting of the brain and spinal cord

cerebroid.definition: Resembling, or analogous to, the cerebrum or brain

cerebrology.definition: The science which treats of the cerebrum or brain

cerebropathy.definition: A hypochondriacal condition verging upon insanity, occurring in those whose brains have been unduly taxed; -- called also brain fag

cerebroscopy.definition: Examination of the brain for the diagnosis of disease; esp., the act or process of diagnosticating the condition of the brain by examination of the interior of the eye (as with an ophthalmoscope)

cerebrose.definition: A sugarlike body obtained by the decomposition of the nitrogenous non-phosphorized principles of the brain

cerebrum.definition: The anterior, and in man the larger, division of the brain; the seat of the reasoning faculties and the will. See Brain

cerecloth.definition: A cloth smeared with melted wax, or with some gummy or glutinous matter

cerement.definition: A cerecloth used for the special purpose of enveloping a dead body when embalmed

ceremonial.definition: Relating to ceremony, or external rite; ritual; according to the forms of established rites
Observant of forms; ceremonious. [In this sense ceremonious is now preferred.]
A system of rules and ceremonies, enjoined by law, or established by custom, in religious worship, social intercourse, or the courts of princes; outward form
The order for rites and forms in the Roman Catholic church, or the book containing the rules prescribed to be observed on solemn occasions

ceremonialism.definition: Adherence to external rites; fondness for ceremony

ceremonially.definition: According to rites and ceremonies; as, a person ceremonially unclean

ceremonious.definition: Consisting of outward forms and rites; ceremonial. [In this sense ceremonial is now preferred.]
According to prescribed or customary rules and forms; devoted to forms and ceremonies; formally respectful; punctilious

ceremoniousness.definition: The quality, or practice, of being ceremonious

ceremony.definition: Ar act or series of acts, often of a symbolical character, prescribed by law, custom, or authority, in the conduct of important matters, as in the performance of religious duties, the transaction of affairs of state, and the celebration of notable events; as, the ceremony of crowning a sovereign; the ceremonies observed in consecrating a church; marriage and baptismal ceremonies
Behavior regulated by strict etiquette; a formal method of performing acts of civility; forms of civility prescribed by custom or authority
A ceremonial symbols; an emblem, as a crown, scepter, garland, etc
A sign or prodigy; a portent

ceres.definition: The daughter of Saturn and Ops or Rhea, the goddess of corn and tillage

ceresin.definition: A white wax, made by bleaching and purifying ozocerite, and used as a substitute for beeswax

cereus.definition: A genus of plants of the Cactus family. They are natives of America, from California to Chili

cerevis.definition: A small visorless cap, worn by members of German student corps. It is made in the corps colors, and usually bears the insignia of the corps

ceria.definition: Cerium oxide, CeO2, a white infusible substance constituting about one per cent of the material of the common incandescent mantle

cerin.definition: A waxy substance extracted by alcohol or ether from cork; sometimes applied also to the portion of beeswax which is soluble in alcohol
A variety of the mineral allanite

cerinthian.definition: One of an ancient religious sect, so called from Cerinthus, a Jew, who attempted to unite the doctrines of Christ with the opinions of the Jews and Gnostics

ceriph.definition: One of the fine lines of a letter, esp. one of the fine cross strokes at the top and bottom of letters

cerise.definition: Cherry-colored; a light bright red; -- applied to textile fabrics, especially silk

cerite.definition: A gastropod shell belonging to the family Cerithiïdæ; -- so called from its hornlike form
A mineral of a brownish of cherry-red color, commonly massive. It is a hydrous silicate of cerium and allied metals

cerium.definition: A rare metallic element, occurring in the minerals cerite, allanite, monazite, etc.  Symbol Ce.  Atomic weight 141.5. It resembles iron in color and luster, but is soft, and both malleable and ductile. It tarnishes readily in the air

cernuous.definition: Inclining or nodding downward; pendulous; drooping; -- said of a bud, flower, fruit, or the capsule of a moss

cero.definition: A large and valuable fish of the Mackerel family, of the genus Scomberomorus.  Two species are found in the West Indies and less commonly on the Atlantic coast of the United States, -- the common cero (Scomberomorus caballa), called also kingfish, and spotted, or king, cero (Scomberomorus regalis)

cerography.definition: The art of making characters or designs in, or with, wax
A method of making stereotype plates from inscribed sheets of wax

cerolite.definition: A hydrous silicate of magnesium, allied to serpentine, occurring in waxlike masses of a yellow or greenish color

ceroma.definition: The unguent (a composition of oil and wax) with which wrestlers were anointed among the ancient Romans
That part of the baths and gymnasia in which bathers and wrestlers anointed themselves

ceromancy.definition: Divination by dropping melted wax in water

ceroon.definition: A bale or package. covered with hide, or with wood bound with hide; as, a ceroon of indigo, cochineal, etc

ceroplastic.definition: Relating to the art of modeling in wax

ceroplastics.definition: The art of modeling in wax

cerosin.definition: A waxy substance obtained from the bark of the sugar cane, and crystallizing in delicate white laminæ

cerotene.definition: A white waxy solid obtained from Chinese wax, and by the distillation of cerotin

cerotic.definition: Pertaining to, or derived from, beeswax or Chinese wax; as, cerotic acid or alcohol

cerotin.definition: A white crystalline substance, C27H55.OH, obtained from Chinese wax, and regarded as an alcohol of the paraffin series; -- called also cerotic alcohol, ceryl alcohol

cerotype.definition: A printing process of engraving on a surface of wax spread on a steel plate, for electrotyping

cerrial.definition: Of or pertaining to the cerris

cerris.definition: A species of oak (Quercus cerris) native in the Orient and southern Europe; -- called also bitter oak and Turkey oak

certain.definition: Assured in mind; having no doubts; free from suspicions concerning
Determined; resolved; -- used with an infinitive
Not to be doubted or denied; established as a fact
Actually existing; sure to happen; inevitable
Not specifically named; indeterminate; indefinite; one or some; -- sometimes used independenty as a noun, and meaning certain persons

certainty.definition: The quality, state, or condition, of being certain
A fact or truth unquestionable established

certhiidae.definition: a natural family of birds cosisting of several species of creepers, such as Certhia americana, the tree creeper

certifiable.definition: presenting symptoms of mental illness sufficient for legal commitment to a mental institution
capable of being guaranteed or certified: a certifiable fact

certificate.definition: A written testimony to the truth of any fact; as, certificate of good behavior
To verify or vouch for by certificate
To furnish with a certificate; as, to certificate the captain of a vessel; a certificated teacher

certified.definition: endorsed authoritatively as having met certain requirements; guranteed; as, certified milk; certified mail; a certified check.  Opposite of uncertified
legally insane according to clinical criteria
holding appropriate documentation and officially on record as qualified to perform a specified function or practice a specified skill

certified check.definition: a check drawn on a bank and bearing marks from that bank guaranteeing that funds have been reserved for payment

certify.definition: To give cetain information to; to assure; to make certain
To give certain information of; to make certain, as a fact; to verify
To testify to in writing; to make a declaration concerning, in writing, under hand, or hand and seal

certiorari.definition: A writ issuing out of chancery, or a superior court, to call up the records of a inferior court, or remove a cause there depending, in order that the party may have more sure and speedy justice, or that errors and irregularities may be corrected. It is obtained upon complaint of a party that he has not received justice, or can not have an impartial trial in the inferior court

cerulein.definition: A fast dyestuff, C20H8O6, made by heating gallein with strong sulphuric acid. It dyes mordanted fabrics green

cerulenin.definition: an antifungal antibiotic, C12H17NO3.  It inhibits the growth of yeasts by interfering with the synthesis of sterols and fatty acids

ceruleum.definition: A greenish blue pigment prepared in various ways, consisting essentially of cobalt stannate. Unlike other cobalt blues, it does not change color by gaslight

cerulific.definition: Producing a blue or sky color

cerumen.definition: The yellow, waxlike secretion from the glands of the external ear; the earwax

ceruminous.definition: Pertaining to, or secreting, cerumen; as, the ceruminous glands

ceruse.definition: White lead, used as a pigment. See White lead, under White

cerused.definition: Washed with a preparation of white lead; as, cerused face

cerusite.definition: Native lead carbonate; a mineral occurring in colorless, white, or yellowish transparent crystals, with an adamantine, also massive and compact

cervelat.definition: An ancient wind instrument, resembling the bassoon in tone

cervical.definition: Of or pertaining to the neck; as, the cervical vertebræ

cervicide.definition: The act of killing deer; deer-slaying

cervid.definition: any member of the family Cervidae, a type of deer distinguished from the Bovidae by the male's having solid deciduous antlers

cervidae.definition: a natural family of deer including the reindeer, moose, elks, muntjacs, and roe deer

cervine.definition: Of or pertaining to the deer, or to the family Cervidæ

cervix.definition: The neck; also, the necklike portion of any part, as of the womb. See Illust. of Bird

cervus.definition: A genus of ruminants, including the red deer and other allied species

ceryl.definition: A radical, C27H55 supposed to exist in several compounds obtained from Chinese wax, beeswax, etc

cesarean section.definition: the operation of taking a child from the womb by cutting through the walls of the abdomen and uterus; -- so called because Julius Cæsar is reported to have been brought into the world by such an operation; -- called also caesarean

cesium.definition: the chemical element of atomic number 55.  It is a univalent element, the most electropositive metal.  Symbol Cs; atomic weight 132.905.  IT has a melting point of 28.4° C

cespitine.definition: An oil obtained by distillation of peat, and containing various members of the pyridine series

cespitose.definition: Having the form a piece of turf, i. e., many stems from one rootstock or from many entangled rootstocks or roots

cespitous.definition: Pertaining to, consisting, of resembling, turf; turfy

cess.definition: To rate; to tax; to assess

cessation.definition: A ceasing or discontinuance, as of action, whether temporary or final; a stop; as, a cessation of the war

cessavit.definition: A writ given by statute to recover lands when the tenant has for two years failed to perform the conditions of his tenure

cesser.definition: a neglect of a tenant to perform services, or make payment, for two years

cession.definition: A yielding, or surrender, as of property or rights, to another person; the act of ceding
The giving up or vacating a benefice by accepting another without a proper dispensation
The voluntary surrender of a person's effects to his creditors to avoid imprisonment

cessionary.definition: Having surrendered the effects; as, a cessionary bankrupt

cessor.definition: One who neglects, for two years, to perform the service by which he holds lands, so that he incurs the danger of the writ of cessavit. See Cessavit

cesspipe.definition: A pipe for carrying off waste water, etc., from a sink or cesspool

cesspool.definition: A cistern in the course, or the termination, of a drain, to collect sedimentary or superfluous matter; a privy vault; any receptacle of filth

cestidae.definition: A family of invertebrates coextensive with the order Cestida; ctenophores having a greatly flattened and elongated body

cestoda.definition: A subclass of parasitic worms of the class Cestoidea.  In some classifications, it is not differentiated from the parent class

cestode.definition: Of or pertaining to the Cestoidea

cestoid.definition: Of or pertaining to the Cestoidea

cestoidea.definition: A class of parasitic worms of the phylum Platyhelminthes (formerly Platelminthes) of which the tapeworms are the most common examples.  The body is flattened, and usually but not always long, and composed of numerous joints or segments, each of which may contain a complete set of male and female reproductive organs. They have neither mouth nor intestine. See Tapeworm

cestraciont.definition: A shark of the genus Cestracion, and of related genera. The posterior teeth form a pavement of bony plates for crushing shellfish. Most of the species are extinct. The Port Jackson shark and a similar one found in California are living examples
Pertaining to, or characteristic of, the genus Cestracion

cestus.definition: A girdle; particularly that of Aphrodite (or Venus) which gave the wearer the power of exciting love
A genus of Ctenophora. The typical species (Cestus Veneris) is remarkable for its brilliant iridescent colors, and its long, girdlelike form
A covering for the hands of boxers, made of leather bands, and often loaded with lead or iron

cetacea.definition: An order of marine mammals, including the whales. Like ordinary mammals they breathe by means of lungs, and bring forth living young which they suckle for some time. The anterior limbs are changed to paddles; the tail flukes are horizontal. There are two living suborders:

cetaceous.definition: Of or pertaining to the Cetacea

cete.definition: One of the Cetacea, or collectively, the Cetacea

cetene.definition: An oily hydrocarbon, C16H32, of the ethylene series, obtained from spermaceti

ceterach.definition: A species of fern with fronds (Asplenium Ceterach)

cetic.definition: Of or pertaining to a whale

cetin.definition: A white, waxy substance, forming the essential part of spermaceti

cetology.definition: The description or natural history of cetaceous animals

cetraric.definition: Pertaining to, or derived from, the lichen, Iceland moss (Cetaria Islandica)

cetrarin.definition: A white substance extracted from the lichen, Iceland moss (Cetraria Islandica). It consists of several ingredients, among which is cetraric acid, a white, crystalline, bitter substance

cetyl.definition: A radical, C16H33, not yet isolated, but supposed to exist in a series of compounds homologous with the ethyl compounds, and derived from spermaceti

cetylic.definition: Of, pertaining to, or derived from, spermaceti

ceylanite.definition: A dingy blue, or grayish black, variety of spinel. It is also called pleonaste

ceylon.definition: the former name of an island republic in the Indian Ocean off the southeast coast of India, now called Sri Lanka.  It is an independent nation with an area of 25,332 sq. mi. and a population of about 14 million people

ceylonese.definition: Of or pertaining to Ceylon; -- since the change of name, replaced by Sri Lankan

cha.definition: Tea; -- the Chinese (Mandarin) name, used generally in early works of travel, and now for a kind of rolled tea used in Central Asia

cha-cha.definition: a modern ballroom dance from Latin America; it uses two slow steps followed by three quick small steps, with swaying movements of the hips, and has many variations of movements based on that rhythm

chabasite.definition: A mineral occuring in glassy rhombohedral crystals, varying in color from white to yellow or red. It is essentially a hydrous silicate of alumina and lime. Called also chabasie

chablis.definition: A white wine made near Chablis, a town in France
a white wine resembling Chablis{1}, but made elsewhere, as in California

chabouk.definition: A long whip, such as is used in the East in the infliction of punishment

chace.definition: To pursue. See Chase v. t

chack.definition: To toss up the head frequently, as a horse to avoid the restraint of the bridle

chacma.definition: A large species of African baboon (Cynocephalus porcarius); -- called also ursine baboon. [See Illust. of Baboon.]

chaconne.definition: An old Spanish dance in moderate three-four measure, like the Passacaglia, which is slower. Both are used by classical composers as themes for variations

chaenopsis.definition: a genus of clinid fishes consisting of the pikeblennies

chaeronea.definition: either of two battles in ancient Greece, one in which Philip of Macedon defeated the Athenians and Thebans (338 BC), or another in which Sulla defeated Mithridates (86 BC)

chaeta.definition: a stiff chitinous seta or bristle especially of an annelid worm

chaetal.definition: of or relating to chaetae (setae or bristles)

chaetetes.definition: A genus of fossil corals, common in the lower Silurian limestones

chaetodont.definition: A marine fish of the family Chætodontidæ. The chætodonts have broad, compressed bodies, and usually bright colors
Of or pertaining to the Chætodonts or the family Chætodontidæ

chaetodontidae.definition: a natural family comprising the butterfly fishes

chaetognath.definition: Of or pertaining to the Chætognatha
any worm of the Chaetognatha; transparent marine worm with horizontal lateral and caudal fins and a row of movable curved spines at each side of the mouth

chaetognatha.definition: a phylum consisting of the arrowworms, a group of small active transparent free-swimming marine worms, of which the genus Sagitta is the type. They have groups of curved spines on each side of the head

chaetognathan.definition: of or pertaining to the Chaetognatha

chaetopoda.definition: A very extensive order of Annelida (segmented worms), characterized by the presence of lateral setæ, or spines, on most or all of the segments.  They are divided into two principal groups: Oligochæta, including the earthworms and allied forms, and Polychæta, including most of the marine species

chaetotaxy.definition: The arrangement of bristles on an insect

chafe.definition: To excite heat in by friction; to rub in order to stimulate and make warm
To excite passion or anger in; to fret; to irritate
To fret and wear by rubbing; as, to chafe a cable
To rub; to come together so as to wear by rubbing; to wear by friction
To be worn by rubbing; as, a cable chafes
To have a feeling of vexation; to be vexed; to fret; to be irritated
Injury or wear caused by friction

chafer.definition: A vessel for heating water; -- hence, a dish or pan
A kind of beetle; the cockchafer. The name is also applied to other species; as, the rose chafer

chafery.definition: An open furnace or forge, in which blooms are heated before being wrought into bars

chafewax.definition: Formerly a chancery officer who fitted wax for sealing writs and other documents

chafeweed.definition: The cudweed (Gnaphalium), used to prevent or cure chafing

chaff.definition: The glumes or husks of grains and grasses separated from the seed by threshing and winnowing, etc
Anything of a comparatively light and worthless character; the refuse part of anything
Straw or hay cut up fine for the food of cattle
The scales or bracts on the receptacle, which subtend each flower in the heads of many Compositæ, as the sunflower
To use light, idle language by way of fun or ridicule; to banter
To make fun of; to turn into ridicule by addressing in ironical or bantering language; to quiz

chaffer.definition: To treat or dispute about a purchase; to bargain; to haggle or higgle; to negotiate
To talk much and idly; to chatter
To buy or sell; to trade in
To exchange; to bandy, as words

chaffinch.definition: A bird of Europe (Fringilla cœlebs), having a variety of very sweet songs, and highly valued as a cage bird; -- called also copper finch

chaffing.definition: The use of light, frivolous language by way of fun or ridicule; raillery; banter

chaffy.definition: Resembling chaff; composed of light dry scales

chafing.definition: The act of rubbing, or wearing by friction; making by rubbing

chagas' disease.definition: a form of trypanosomiasis caused by infection with Trypamosoma cruzi, found principally in South America.  It is transmitted by certain species of reduviid bugs, and has natural reservoirs in dogs, armadillos, rodents and other domestic and wild mammals

chagres fever.definition: A form of malarial fever occurring along the Chagres River, Panama

chagrin.definition: To excite ill-humor in; to vex; to mortify; as, he was not a little chagrined

chagrined.definition: feeling vexed, especially due to feeling inferior or unworthy and hence embarrassed; as, chagrined at the poor sales of his book

chain.definition: A series of links or rings, usually of metal, connected, or fitted into one another, used for various purposes, as of support, of restraint, of ornament, of the exertion and transmission of mechanical power, etc
That which confines, fetters, or secures, as a chain; a bond; as, the chains of habit
A series of things linked together; or a series of things connected and following each other in succession; as, a chain of mountains; a chain of events or ideas
An instrument which consists of links and is used in measuring land
Iron links bolted to the side of a vessel to bold the dead-eyes connected with the shrouds; also, the channels
The warp threads of a web
To fasten, bind, or connect with a chain; to fasten or bind securely, as with a chain; as, to chain a bulldog
To keep in slavery; to enslave
To protect by drawing a chain across, as a harbor

chain pump.definition: A pump consisting of an endless chain, running over a drum or wheel by which it is moved, and dipping below the water to be raised. The chain has at intervals disks or lifts which fit the tube through which the ascending part passes and carry the water to the point of discharge

chain stitch.definition: An ornamental stitch like the links of a chain; -- used in crocheting, sewing, and embroidery
A stitch in which the looping of the thread or threads forms a chain on the under side of the work; the loop stitch, as distinguished from the lock stitch. See Stitch

chain tie.definition: A tie consisting of a series of connected iron bars or rods

chain wheel.definition: A chain pulley, or sprocket wheel
An inversion of the chain pump, by which it becomes a motor driven by water

chained.definition: bound with chains; as, prisoners chained together to prevent escape

chainless.definition: Having no chain; not restrained or fettered

chainlike.definition: having a form resembling a chain; as, chainlike clusters of bacteria

chains.definition: metal shackles connected by chains, used to bind hands or legs; as, he was kept two weeks in chains

chainsaw.definition: a portable power saw having teeth that are linked to form an endless chain, rotated about two pivot points by a power mechanism, such as an electric motor or a gasoline engine

chainwork.definition: Work looped or linked after the manner of a chain; chain stitch work

chair.definition: A movable single seat with a back
An official seat, as of a chief magistrate or a judge, but esp. that of a professor; hence, the office itself
The presiding officer of an assembly; a chairman; as, to address the chair
A vehicle for one person; either a sedan borne upon poles, or two-wheeled carriage, drawn by one horse; a gig
An iron block used on railways to support the rails and secure them to the sleepers
To carry publicly in a chair in triumph
To function as chairperson of (a meeting, committee, etc.); as, he chaired the meeting

chairlift.definition: a ski lift on which riders are seated

chairman.definition: The presiding officer of a committee, or of a public or private meeting, or of any organized body
One whose business it is to cary a chair or sedan

chairmanship.definition: The office of a chairman of a meeting or organized body

chairperson.definition: the officer who presides at the meetings of an organization; -- same as chair{3} or chairman{1}, but used to achieve a sex-neutral register

chairwoman.definition: a female officer who presides at the meetings of a committee, meeting, or organization; a female chairperson

chaise.definition: A two-wheeled carriage for two persons, with a calash top, and the body hung on leather straps, or thorough-braces. It is usually drawn by one horse

chaja.definition: The crested screamer of Brazil (Palamedea chavaria syn. Chauna chavaria), so called in imitation of its notes; -- called also chauna, and faithful kamichi. It is often domesticated and is useful in guarding other poultry. See Kamichi

chalaza.definition: The place on an ovule, or seed, where its outer coats cohere with each other and the nucleus
A spiral band of thickened albuminous substance which exists in the white of the bird's egg, and serves to maintain the yolk in its position; the treadle

chalazal.definition: Of or pertaining to the chalaza

chalazion.definition: A small circumscribed tumor of the eyelid caused by retention of secretion, and by inflammation of the Melbomian glands

chalazogamy.definition: A process of fecundation in which the pollen tube penetrates to the embryosac through the tissue of the chalaza, instead of entering through the micropyle. It was originally discovered by Treub in Casuarina, and has since been found to occur regularly in the families Betulaceæ and Juglandaceæ. Partial chalazogamy is found in Ulmus, the tube here penetrating the nucleus midway between the chalaza and micropyle

chalcanthite.definition: Native blue vitriol. See Blue vitriol, under Blue

chalcedony.definition: A cryptocrystalline, translucent variety of quartz, having usually a whitish color, and a luster nearly like wax

chalchihuitl.definition: The Mexican name for turquoise. See Turquoise

chalcid fly.definition: One of a numerous family of hymenopterous insects (Chalcididæ. Many are gallflies, others are parasitic on insects

chalcidian.definition: One of a tropical family of snakelike lizards (Chalcidæ), having four small or rudimentary legs

chalcis.definition: the type genus of the Chalcididae

chalcocite.definition: Native copper sulphide, called also copper glance, and vitreous copper; a mineral of a black color and metallic luster

chalcographer.definition: An engraver on copper or brass; hence, an engraver of copper plates for printing upon paper

chalcography.definition: The act or art of engraving on copper or brass, especially of engraving for printing

chalcopyrite.definition: Copper pyrites, or yellow copper ore; a common ore of copper, containing copper, iron, and sulphur. It occurs massive and in tetragonal crystals of a bright brass yellow color

chaldaism.definition: An idiom or peculiarity in the Chaldee dialect

chaldrich.definition: A kind of bird; the oyster catcher

chaldron.definition: An English dry measure, being, at London, 36 bushels heaped up, or its equivalent weight, and more than twice as much at Newcastle. Now used exclusively for coal and coke

chalet.definition: A herdsman's hut in the mountains of Switzerland
A summer cottage or country house in the Swiss mountains; any country house built in the style of the Swiss cottages

chalice.definition: A cup or bowl; especially, the cup used in the sacrament of the Lord's Supper

chaliced.definition: Having a calyx or cup; cup-shaped

chalk.definition: A soft, earthy substance, of a white, grayish, or yellowish white color, consisting of calcium carbonate, and having the same composition as common limestone
Finely prepared chalk, used as a drawing implement; also, by extension, a compound, as of clay and black lead, or the like, used in the same manner. See Crayon
To rub or mark with chalk
To manure with chalk, as land
To make white, as with chalk; to make pale; to bleach

chalk line.definition: a string impregnated with powdered chalk, used in construction to mark a straight line on a surface, such as a wall.  The string is held taut on the surface between the two end points of the line to be made, the center of the line is drawn away from the surface, and the string is released and snapped against the surface, leaving a line of chalk in the desired location
the line of chalk on a surface left by a chalk line{1}

chalkboard.definition: a dark sheet of slate used as a surface for writing on, with chalk

chalkstone.definition: A chalklike concretion, consisting mainly of urate of sodium, found in and about the small joints, in the external ear, and in other situations, in those affected with gout; a tophus

chalky.definition: Consisting of, or resembling, chalk; containing chalk; as, a chalky cliff; a chalky taste

challenge.definition: An invitation to engage in a contest or controversy of any kind; a defiance; specifically, a summons to fight a duel; also, the letter or message conveying the summons
The act of a sentry in halting any one who appears at his post, and demanding the countersign
The opening and crying of hounds at first finding the scent of their game

An exception to a juror or to a member of a court martial, coupled with a demand that he should be held incompetent to act; the claim of a party that a certain person or persons shall not sit in trial upon him or his cause
An exception to a person as not legally qualified to vote. The challenge must be made when the ballot is offered
To call to a contest of any kind; to call to answer; to defy
To call, invite, or summon to answer for an offense by personal combat
To claim as due; to demand as a right
To question or demand the countersign from (one who attempts to pass the lines); as, the sentinel challenged us, with  “Who comes there?”
To take exception to; question; as, to challenge the accuracy of a statement or of a quotation
To object to or take exception to, as to a juror, or member of a court
To object to the reception of the vote of, as on the ground that the person in not qualified as a voter
To assert a right; to claim a place

challenged.definition: having doubts expressed about its truth
handicapped or disabled; -- used as a euphemism, especially in combinations; as, physically challenged; mentally challenged

challenging.definition: requiring full use of one's abilities or resources; as, challenging task
disposed to or engaged in defiance of established authority

challis.definition: A soft and delicate woolen, or woolen and silk, fabric, for ladies' dresses

chalybean.definition: Of or pertaining to the Chalybes, an ancient people of Pontus in Asia Minor, celebrated for working in iron and steel
Of superior quality and temper; -- applied to steel

chalybeate.definition: Impregnated with salts of iron; having a taste like iron; as, chalybeate springs
Any water, liquid, or medicine, into which iron enters as an ingredient

chalybeous.definition: Steel blue; of the color of tempered steel

chalybite.definition: Native iron carbonate; -- usually called siderite

cham.definition: The sovereign prince of Tartary; -- now usually written khan

Liberality to the poor and the suffering, to benevolent institutions, or to worthy causes; generosity
Whatever is bestowed gratuitously on the needy or suffering for their relief; alms; any act of kindness
A charitable institution, or a gift to create and support such an institution; as, Lady Margaret's charity
Eleemosynary appointments [grants or devises] including relief of the poor or friendless, education, religious culture, and public institutions

charivari.definition: A mock serenade of discordant noises, made with kettles, tin horns, etc., designed to annoy and insult; -- called also shivaree

chark.definition: To burn to a coal; to char

charlatan.definition: One who prates much in his own favor, and makes unwarrantable pretensions; a quack; an impostor; an empiric; a mountebank

charlatanic.definition: Of or like a charlatan; making undue pretension; empirical; pretentious; quackish

charlatanry.definition: Undue pretensions to skill; quackery; wheedling; empiricism

charles's wain.definition: The group of seven stars, commonly called the Big Dipper, in the constellation Ursa Major, or Great Bear. See Ursa major, under Ursa

charlie.definition: A familiar nickname or substitute for Charles

A short, pointed beard, like that worn by Charles I
As a proper name, a fox; -- so called in fables and familiar literature

charlock.definition: A cruciferous plant (Brassica sinapistrum) with yellow flowers; wild mustard. It is troublesome in grain fields. Called also chardock, chardlock, chedlock, and kedlock

charlotte.definition: A kind of pie or pudding made by lining a dish with slices of bread, and filling it with bread soaked in milk, and baked

charm.definition: A word or combination of words sung or spoken in the practice of magic; a magical combination of words, characters, etc.; an incantation
That which exerts an irresistible power to please and attract; that which fascinates; any alluring quality
Anything worn for its supposed efficacy to the wearer in averting ill or securing good fortune
Any small decorative object worn on the person, as a seal, a key, a silver whistle, or the like. Bunches of charms are often worn at the watch chain
a property of certain quarks which may take the value of +1, -1 or 0
To make music upon; to tune
To subdue, control, or summon by incantation or supernatural influence; to affect by magic
To subdue or overcome by some secret power, or by that which gives pleasure; to allay; to soothe
To attract irresistibly; to delight exceedingly; to enchant; to fascinate
To protect with, or make invulnerable by, spells, charms, or supernatural influences; as, a charmed life
To use magic arts or occult power; to make use of charms
To act as, or produce the effect of, a charm; to please greatly; to be fascinating

charmer.definition: One who charms, or has power to charm; one who uses the power of enchantment; a magician
One who delights and attracts the affections

charming.definition: Pleasing the mind or senses in a high degree; delighting; fascinating; attractive

charnel.definition: Containing the bodies of the dead
A charnel house; a grave; a cemetery

charon.definition: The son of Erebus and Nox, whose office it was to ferry the souls of the dead over the Styx, a river of the infernal regions

charpie.definition: Straight threads obtained by unraveling old linen cloth; -- used for surgical dressings

charqui.definition: Jerked beef; beef cut into long strips and dried in the wind and sun

charras.definition: The gum resin of the hemp plant (Cannabis sativa). Same as Churrus

charry.definition: Pertaining to charcoal, or partaking of its qualities

chart.definition: A sheet of paper, pasteboard, or the like, on which information is exhibited, esp. when the information is arranged in tabular form; as, an historical chart

A map; esp., a hydrographic or marine map; a map on which is projected a portion of water and the land which it surrounds, or by which it is surrounded, intended especially for the use of seamen; as, the United States Coast Survey charts; the English Admiralty charts
To lay down in a chart; to map; to delineate; as, to chart a coast

charta.definition: Material on which instruments, books, etc., are written; parchment or paper

chartaceous.definition: Resembling paper or parchment; of paper-like texture; papery

charte.definition: The constitution, or fundamental law, of the French monarchy, as established on the restoration of Louis XVIII., in 1814

charter.definition: A written evidence in due form of things done or granted, contracts made, etc., between man and man; a deed, or conveyance
An instrument in writing, from the sovereign power of a state or country, executed in due form, bestowing rights, franchises, or privileges

An act of a legislative body creating a municipal or other corporation and defining its powers and privileges. Also, an instrument in writing from the constituted authorities of an order or society (as the Freemasons), creating a lodge and defining its powers
A special privilege, immunity, or exemption
The letting or hiring a vessel by special contract, or the contract or instrument whereby a vessel is hired or let; as, a ship is offered for sale or charter. See Charter party, below
To hire or let by charter, as a ship. See Charter party, under Charter, n

chartered.definition: Granted or established by charter; having, or existing under, a charter; having a privilege by charter
Hired or let by charter, as a ship

charterer.definition: One who charters; esp. one who hires a ship for a voyage

charterhouse.definition: A well known public school and charitable foundation in the building once used as a Carthusian monastery (Chartreuse) in London

chartism.definition: The principles of a political party in England (1838-48), which contended for universal suffrage, the vote by ballot, annual parliaments, equal electoral districts, and other radical reforms, as set forth in a document called the People's Charter

chartist.definition: A supporter or partisan of chartism

chartless.definition: Without a chart; having no guide

chartomancy.definition: Divination by written paper or by cards

chartometer.definition: An instrument for measuring charts or maps

chartreuse.definition: A Carthusian monastery; esp. La Grande Chartreuse, mother house of the order, in the mountains near Grenoble, France

charwoman.definition: A woman hired for odd work or for single days

chary.definition: Careful; wary; cautious; not rash, or reckless; as, the latest internet IPO's were shunned by investors made chary by the poor performance of the first wave of companies that went public
Saving; frugal; sparing; not spendthrift; -- often used with of; as, chary of his praise

charybdis.definition: A dangerous whirlpool on the coast of Sicily opposite Scylla on the Italian coast. It is personified as a female monster. See Scylla

chasable.definition: Capable of being chased; fit for hunting

chase.definition: To pursue for the purpose of killing or taking, as an enemy, or game; to hunt

To pursue eagerly, as hunters pursue game

That which is pursued or hunted

A rectangular iron frame in which pages or columns of type are imposed

To ornament (a surface of metal) by embossing, cutting away parts, and the like
To cut, so as to make a screw thread

chased.definition: a person who is being chased; as, better to be the chaser than the chased

chasing.definition: The art of ornamenting metal by means of chasing tools; also, a piece of ornamental work produced in this way

chasm.definition: A deep opening made by disruption, as a breach in the earth or a rock; a yawning abyss; a cleft; a fissure

chasse.definition: A movement in dancing, as across or to the right or left

chasselas.definition: A white grape, esteemed for the table

chassepot.definition: A kind of breechloading, center-fire rifle, or improved needle gun

chassis.definition: A traversing base frame, or movable railway, along which the carriage of a barbette or casemate gun moves backward and forward. [See Gun carriage.]

chaste.definition: Pure from unlawful sexual intercourse; virtuous; continent

Pure in design and expression; correct; free from barbarisms or vulgarisms; refined; simple; as, a chaste style in composition or art

chastiser.definition: One who chastises; a punisher; a corrector

chastity.definition: The state of being chaste; purity of body; freedom from unlawful sexual intercourse

chasuble.definition: The outer vestment worn by the priest in saying Mass, consisting, in the Roman Catholic Church, of a broad, flat, back piece, and a narrower front piece, the two connected over the shoulders only. The back has usually a large cross, the front an upright bar or pillar, designed to be emblematical of Christ's sufferings. In the Greek Church the chasuble is a large round mantle

chat.definition: To talk in a light and familiar manner; to converse without form or ceremony; to gossip

A bird of the genus Icteria, allied to the warblers, in America.  The best known species are the yellow-breasted chat (Icteria viridis), and the long-tailed chat (Icteria longicauda). In Europe the name is given to several birds of the family Saxicolidæ, as the stonechat, and whinchat
A twig, cone, or little branch. See Chit

chateau.definition: A castle or a fortress in France

To make a noise by rapid collisions
To utter rapidly, idly, or indistinctly
Sounds like those of a magpie or monkey; idle talk; rapid, thoughtless talk; jabber; prattle

chattering.definition: The act or habit of talking idly or rapidly, or of making inarticulate sounds; the sounds so made; noise made by the collision of the teeth; chatter

The flute of a bagpipe. See Chanter, n., 3

It originated in the village of Chautauqua, N. Y., in 1874, and was popular in the late 19th and early 20th centuries.  Also, a meeting similar to this

exaggerated and unreasoning partisanship to any group or cause; -- as, male chauvinism, i.e. belief in the superiority of males

As much as is put in the mouth at once; a chew; a quid

chebec.definition: A small American bird (Empidonax minimus); the least flycatcher

chechoslovak.definition: a native or inhabitant of Czechoslovakia; a Czechoslovakian

To make a checkered pattern upon
To make a stop; to pause; -- with at
To clash or interfere
To act as a curb or restraint
To crack or gape open, as wood in drying; or to crack in small checks, as varnish, paint, etc

Checkered; designed in checks

check in.definition: To register as a guest at a hotel, inn, motel. etc.   Converse of check out

check-in.definition: The act of registering as a guest at a hotel, inn, motel. etc; the act of checking in.  Used also attributively, as the check-in counter at a hotel

checkage.definition: The act of checking; as, the checkage of a name or of an item in a list

checked.definition: Held back from some action especially by force
having a pattern of alternating dark and light squares in rows and columns

checker.definition: To mark with small squares like a checkerboard, as by crossing stripes of different colors

A piece in the game of draughts or checkers
A pattern in checks; a single check

checkerberry.definition: A spicy plant and its bright red berry; the wintergreen (Gaultheria procumbens).  Also incorrectly applied to the partridge berry (Mitchella repens)

checkerbloom.definition: a perennial purple-flowered wild mallow of West North America (Sidalcea malviflora) that is also cultivated

checkerboard.definition: A board with sixty-four squares of alternate color, used for playing checkers, chess, or draughts

checkered.definition: Marked with alternate squares or checks of different color or material

checkless.definition: That can not be checked or restrained

To defeat completely; to terminate; to thwart

checkout counter.definition: A counter in a supermarket where one pays for one's purchases
a counter in a supermarket where you pay for your purchases

checkpoint.definition: a place (as at a frontier) where travellers are stopped for inspection and clearance

checkroll.definition: A list of servants in a household; -- called also chequer roll

checkstring.definition: A cord by which a person in a carriage or horse car may signal to the driver

checkwork.definition: Anything made so as to form alternate squares like those of a checkerboard

checky.definition: Divided into small alternating squares of two tinctures; -- said of the field or of an armorial bearing

cheddar.definition: Of or pertaining to, or made at, Cheddar, in England; as, Cheddar cheese

cheek.definition: The side of the face below the eye

The branches of a bridle bit

To be impudent or saucy to

cheeked.definition: Having a cheek; -- used in composition

cheep.definition: To chirp, as a young bird
To give expression to in a chirping tone
A chirp, peep, or squeak, as of a young bird or mouse

cheer.definition: The face; the countenance or its expression
Feeling; spirit; state of mind or heart
That which promotes good spirits or cheerfulness; provisions prepared for a feast; entertainment; as, a table loaded with good cheer
A shout, hurrah, or acclamation, expressing joy enthusiasm, applause, favor, etc

To be in any state or temper of mind
To utter a shout or shouts of applause, triumph, etc

cheerer.definition: One who cheers; one who, or that which, gladdens

cheerful.definition: Having or showing good spirits or joy; cheering; cheery; contented; happy; joyful; lively; animated; willing

cheerfulness.definition: Good spirits; a state of moderate joy or gayety; alacrity

cheeringly.definition: In a manner to cheer or encourage

cheery.definition: Displaying evident cheerfulness; cheerful; lively; gay; bright; pleasant; as, a cheery person; a cheery hello

cheese.definition: The curd of milk, coagulated usually with rennet, separated from the whey, and pressed into a solid mass in a hoop or mold
A mass of pomace, or ground apples, pressed together in the form of a cheese

cheeseboard.definition: a board on which cheeses are served

cheeseburger.definition: a hamburger with melted cheese on it

cheesecloth.definition: A thin, loosely-woven cotton cloth of a gauze texture, such as is used in pressing cheese curds

cheeseflower.definition: an erect or decumbent Old World perennial (Malva sylvestris) with axillary clusters of rosy-purple flowers; introduced into the U. S

cheeselep.definition: A bag in which rennet is kept

cheeseparing.definition: A thin portion of the rind of a cheese

cheesy.definition: Having the nature, qualities, taste, form, consistency, or appearance of cheese

cheewink.definition: the common rufous-sided towhee of eastern North America, Pipilo erythrophthalmus

chef.definition: The head cook of large establishment, as a club, a family, etc

chef-d'oeuvre.definition: A masterpiece; a capital work in art, literature, etc

chelate.definition: a compound formed by combination of a metal ion in solution with a compound containing heteroatoms (such as oxygen or nitrogen), in which at least two heteroatoms are bound to the metal.  The bonds may be covalent or non-covalent.  Chelates in some cases have very low dissociation constants, and organic compounds (chelating agents) which form such chelates are therefore used to reduce the concentration of free metal ions in solution

chelated.definition: combined with a chelator so as to form a chelate; -- of metal ions

chelating agent.definition: a compound which forms a chelate with a metal ion

chelation.definition: the process of removing a heavy metal from a solution by means of a chelate
the process of forming a ring by forming one or more hydrogen bonds

chelerythrine.definition: An alkaloidal principle obtained from the celandine, and named from the red color of its salts. It is a colorless crystalline substance, and acts as an acrid narcotic poison. It is identical with sanguinarine

chelicera.definition: One of the anterior pair of mouth organs, terminated by a pincherlike claw, in scorpions and allied Arachnida. They are homologous with the falcers of spiders, and probably with the mandibles of insects

chelidon.definition: The hollow at the flexure of the arm

chelidonic.definition: Of, pertaining to, or derived from, the celandine

chelidonium.definition: a genu having only one species; the greater celandine

chelidonius.definition: A small stone taken from the gizzard of a young swallow. -- anciently worn as a medicinal charm

cheliferous.definition: Having cheliform claws, like a crab

cheliform.definition: Having a movable joint or finger closing against a preceding joint or a projecting part of it, so that the whole may be used for grasping, as the claw of a crab; pincherlike

chelone.definition: A genus of hardy perennial flowering plants, of the order Scrophulariaceæ, natives of North America; -- called also snakehead, turtlehead, shellflower, etc

chelonethida.definition: an order comprising the false scorpions

chelonia.definition: An order of reptiles, including the tortoises and turtles, peculiar in having a part of the vertebræ, ribs, and sternum united with the dermal plates so as to form a firm shell. The jaws are covered by a horny beak. See Reptilia; also, Illust. in Appendix

chelonian.definition: Of or pertaining to animals of the tortoise kind

cheloniidae.definition: a natural family including the green turtles; hawksbills

chelura.definition: A genus of marine amphipod crustacea, which bore into and sometimes destroy timber

chelyabinsk.definition: a city in the Asian part of Russia

chelydridae.definition: a natural family comprising the snapping turtles

chemic.definition: A solution of chloride of lime

chemical.definition: Pertaining to chemistry; characterized or produced by the forces and operations of chemistry; employed in the processes of chemistry; as, chemical changes; chemical combinations
A substance used for producing a chemical effect; a reagent

chemically.definition: According to chemical principles; by chemical process or operation

chemigraphy.definition: Any mechanical engraving process depending upon chemical action; specif., a process of zinc etching not employing photography

chemiloon.definition: A garment for women, consisting of chemise and drawers united in one

chemise.definition: A shift, or undergarment, worn by women
A wall that lines the face of a bank or earthwork

chemisette.definition: An under-garment, worn by women, usually covering the neck, shoulders, and breast

chemism.definition: The force exerted between the atoms of elementary substance whereby they unite to form chemical compounds; chemical attraction; affinity; -- sometimes used as a general expression for chemical activity or relationship

chemisorptive.definition: having the capacity to adsorb by chemical as contrasted with physical forces

chemist.definition: A person versed in chemistry or given to chemical investigation; an analyst; a maker or seller of chemicals or drugs

chemist's.definition: a retail shop where medicine and other articles are sold; a drugstore

chemistry.definition: That branch of science which treats of the composition of substances, and of the changes which they undergo in consequence of alterations in the constitution of the molecules, which depend upon variations of the number, kind, or mode of arrangement, of the constituent atoms. These atoms are not assumed to be indivisible, but merely the finest grade of subdivision hitherto attained. Chemistry deals with the changes in the composition and constitution of molecules. See Atom, Molecule
An application of chemical theory and method to the consideration of some particular subject; as, the chemistry of iron; the chemistry of indigo

chemitype.definition: One of a number of processes by which an impression from an engraved plate is obtained in relief, to be used for printing on an ordinary printing press

chemolysis.definition: A term sometimes applied to the decomposition of organic substance into more simple bodies, by the use of chemical agents alone

chemosis.definition: Inflammatory swelling of the conjunctival tissue surrounding the cornea

chemosmosis.definition: Chemical action taking place through an intervening membrane

chemosmotic.definition: Pertaining to, or produced by, chemosmosis

chemosorption.definition: adsorption (especially when irreversible) by means of chemical instead of physical forces; as, chemosorption of gaseous nitrogen on iron catalysts

chemosynthesis.definition: Synthesis of organic compounds by energy derived from chemical changes or reactions. Chemosynthesis of carbohydrates occurs in the nitrite bacteria through the oxidation of ammonia to nitrous acid, and in the nitrate bacteria through the conversion of nitrous into nitric acid

chemotaxis.definition: The sensitiveness exhibited by small free-swimming organisms, as bacteria, zoospores of algæ, etc., to chemical substances held in solution. They may be attracted (positive chemotaxis) or repelled (negative chemotaxis)

chemotherapeutic.definition: of or pertaining to chemotherapy; using chemotherapy; having properties beneficial for chemotherapy

chemotherapy.definition: the use of chemical agents to treat or control disease (or mental illness); -- also used especially in reference to the use of chemicals to treat cancer

chemung period.definition: A subdivision in the upper part of the Devonian system in America, so named from the Chemung River, along which the rocks are well developed. It includes the Portage and Chemung groups or epochs. See the Diagram under Geology

chen.definition: a wild goose having white adult plumage

chenfish.definition: small silvery marine food fish (Genyonemus lineatus) found off California

cheng.definition: A chinese reed instrument, with tubes, blown by the mouth

chenille.definition: Tufted cord, of silk or worsted, for the trimming of ladies' dresses, for embroidery and fringes, and for the weft of Chenille rugs

chenomorphae.definition: An order of birds, including the swans, ducks, geese, flamingoes and screamers

chenopodiales.definition: an order which corresponds approximately to the older group Centrospermae

chenopodium.definition: a genus of plants comprising the goosefoots and including the pigweed

cheoplasty.definition: molding artificial teeth using low-fusing metals or alloys

cherimoyer.definition: A small downy-leaved tree (Anona Cherimolia), with fragrant flowers. It is a native of Peru
Its delicious fruit, which is succulent, dark purple, and similar to the custard apple of the West Indies

cherish.definition: To treat with tenderness and affection; to nurture with care; to protect and aid
To hold dear; to embrace with interest; to indulge; to encourage; to foster; to promote; as, to cherish religious principle

cherokees.definition: An Appalachian tribe of Indians, formerly inhabiting the region about the head waters of the Tennessee River. They are now mostly settled in the Indian Territory, and have become one of the most civilized of the Indian Tribes

cheroot.definition: A kind of cigar, originally brought from Manila, in the Philippine Islands; now often made of inferior or adulterated tobacco

cherry.definition: A tree or shrub of the genus Prunus (Which also includes the plum) bearing a fleshy drupe with a bony stone
The fruit of the cherry tree, a drupe of various colors and flavors
The timber of the cherry tree, esp. of the black cherry, used in cabinetmaking, etc
A peculiar shade of red, like that of a cherry
Like a red cherry in color; ruddy; blooming; as, a cherry lip; cherry cheeks

cherrystone.definition: small quahog larger than a littleneck

chersonese.definition: A peninsula; a tract of land nearly surrounded by water, but united to a larger tract by a neck of land or isthmus; as, the Cimbric Chersonese, or Jutland; the Tauric Chersonese, or Crimea

chert.definition: An impure, massive, flintlike quartz or hornstone, of a dull color

cherub.definition: A mysterious composite being, the winged footstool and chariot of the Almighty, described in Ezekiel i. and x
A symbolical winged figure of unknown form used in connection with the mercy seat of the Jewish Ark and Temple

One of a order of angels, variously represented in art. In European painting the cherubim have been shown as blue, to denote knowledge, as distinguished from the seraphim (see Seraph), and in later art the children's heads with wings are generally called cherubs
A beautiful child; -- so called because artists have represented cherubs as beautiful children

cherubic.definition: Of or pertaining to cherubs; angelic

cherubim.definition: The Hebrew plural of Cherub.. Cf. Seraphim

cherup.definition: To make a short, shrill, cheerful sound; to chirp. See Chirrup
To excite or urge on by making a short, shrill, cheerful sound; to cherup to. See Chirrup
A short, sharp, cheerful noise; a chirp; a chirrup; as, the cherup of a cricket

chervil.definition: A plant (Anthriscus cerefolium) with pinnately divided aromatic leaves, of which several curled varieties are used in soups and salads

chess.definition: A game played on a chessboard, by two persons, with two differently colored sets of men, sixteen in each set. Each player has a king, a queen, two bishops, two knights, two castles or rooks, and eight pawns

A species of brome grass (Bromus secalinus) which is a troublesome weed in wheat fields, and is often erroneously regarded as degenerate or changed wheat; it bears a very slight resemblance to oats, and if reaped and ground up with wheat, so as to be used for food, is said to produce narcotic effects; -- called also cheat and Willard's bromus

chess-apple.definition: The wild service of Europe (Purus torminalis)

chessboard.definition: The board used in the game of chess, having eight rows of alternate light and dark squares, eight in each row. See Checkerboard

chessel.definition: The wooden mold in which cheese is pressed

chesses.definition: The platforms, consisting of two or more planks doweled together, for the flooring of a temporary military bridge

chessman.definition: A piece used in the game of chess

chesstree.definition: A piece of oak bolted perpendicularly on the side of a vessel, to aid in drawing down and securing the clew of the mainsail

chessy copper.definition: The mineral azurite, found in fine crystallization at Chessy, near Lyons; called also chessylite

chest.definition: A large box of wood, or other material, having, like a trunk, a lid, but no covering of skin, leather, or cloth
The part of the body inclosed by the ribs and breastbone; the thorax
A case in which certain goods, as tea, opium, etc., are transported; hence, the quantity which such a case contains
A tight receptacle or box, usually for holding gas, steam, liquids, etc.; as, the steam chest of an engine; the wind chest of an organ
To deposit in a chest; to hoard

chest founder.definition: A rheumatic affection of the muscles of the breast and fore legs of a horse, affecting motion and respiration

chested.definition: Having (such) a chest; -- in composition; as, broad-chested; narrow-chested

chesterfield.definition: a fitted overcoat with a velvet collar

chesterlite.definition: A variety of feldspar found in crystals in the county of Chester, Pennsylvania

chestnut.definition: The edible nut of a forest tree (Castanea vesce) of Europe and America. Commonly two or more of the nuts grow in a prickly bur
The tree itself, or its light, coarse-grained timber, used for ornamental work, furniture, etc
A bright brown color, like that of the nut
The horse chestnut (often so used in England)
One of the round, or oval, horny plates on the inner sides of the legs of the horse, and allied animals
Of or pertaining of a chestnut; of a reddish brown color; as, chestnut curls

chesty.definition: marked by a large or well-developed chest
having or showing feelings of unwarranted importance out of overbearing pride; as, chesty as a peacock

chetvert.definition: A measure of grain equal to 0.7218 of an imperial quarter, or 5.95 Winchester bushels

cheval.definition: A horse; hence, a support or frame

cheval-de-frise.definition: A piece of timber or an iron barrel traversed with iron-pointed spikes or spears, five or six feet long, used to defend a passage, stop a breach, or impede the advance of cavalry, etc

chevalier.definition: A horseman; a knight; a gallant young man
A member of certain orders of knighthood

cheve.definition: To come to an issue; to turn out; to succeed; as, to cheve well in a enterprise

cheveril.definition: Soft leather made of kid skin. Fig.: Used as a symbol of flexibility

cheverliize.definition: To make as pliable as kid leather

chevet.definition: The extreme end of the chancel or choir; properly the round or polygonal part

cheviot.definition: A valuable breed of mountain sheep in Scotland, which takes its name from the Cheviot hills
A woolen fabric, for men's clothing

chevrette.definition: A machine for raising guns or mortar into their carriages

chevron.definition: One of the nine honorable ordinaries, consisting of two broad bands of the width of the bar, issuing, respectively from the dexter and sinister bases of the field and conjoined at its center
A distinguishing mark, above the elbow, on the sleeve of a non-commissioned officer's coat
A zigzag molding, or group of moldings, common in Norman architecture

chevroned.definition: Having a chevron; decorated with an ornamental figure of a zigzag from

chevronel.definition: A bearing like a chevron, but of only half its width

chevronwise.definition: In the manner of a chevron; as, the field may be divided chevronwise

chevrotain.definition: A small ruminant of the family Tragulidæ a allied to the musk deer. It inhabits Africa and the East Indies. See Kanchil

chevvy.definition: to repeatedly cause annoyance or concern to; to chevy; -- same as chivy

chevy.definition: The game of prisoners' base. See Base, n., 24

chew.definition: To bite and grind with the teeth; to masticate
To ruminate mentally; to meditate on
To perform the action of biting and grinding with the teeth; to ruminate; to meditate
That which is chewed; that which is held in the mouth at once; a cud

chewing.definition: biting your food in your mouth so it becomes soft enough to swallow

chewink.definition: An american bird (Pipilo erythrophthalmus) of the Finch family, so called from its note; -- called also rufous-sided towhee, towhee, towhee bunting and ground robin

cheyennes.definition: A warlike tribe of indians, related to the blackfeet, formerly inhabiting the region of Wyoming, but now mostly on reservations in the Indian Territory. They are noted for their horsemanship

chian.definition: Of or pertaining to Chios, an island in the Ægean Sea

chianti.definition: a dry red Italian table wine from the Chianti region of Tuscany

chiaroscurist.definition: A painter who cares for and studies light and shade rather than color

chiaroscuro.definition: The arrangement of light and dark parts in a work of art, such as a drawing or painting, whether in monochrome or in color

chiasm.definition: A commissure; an intersection or crossing of two tracts; especially, the optic commissure, or crucial union of the optic nerves

chiasmal.definition: of or pertaining to a chiasma

chiasmus.definition: An inversion of the order of words or phrases, when repeated or subsequently referred to in a sentence

chiastolite.definition: A variety of andalusite; -- called also macle. The tessellated appearance of a cross section is due to the symmetrical arrangement of impurities in the crystal

chibouque.definition: A Turkish pipe, usually with a mouthpiece of amber, a stem, four or five feet long and not pliant, of some valuable wood, and a bowl of baked clay

chic.definition: Original and in good taste or form; stylish; in current fashion, fashionable

chica.definition: A red coloring matter. extracted from the Bignonia Chica, used by some tribes of South American Indians to stain the skin
A fermented liquor or beer made in South American from a decoction of maize
A popular Moorish, Spanish, and South American dance, said to be the original of the fandango, etc

chicalote.definition: A Mexican prickly poppy (Argemone platyceras), which has migrated into California

chicane.definition: The use of artful subterfuge, designed to draw away attention from the merits of a case or question; -- specifically applied to legal proceedings; trickery; chicanery; caviling; sophistry
In bridge, the holding of a hand without trumps, or the hand itself. It counts as simple honors
To use shifts, cavils, or artifices

chicanery.definition: Mean or unfair artifice to perplex a cause and obscure the truth; stratagem; sharp practice; sophistry

chichevache.definition: A fabulous cow of enormous size, whose food was patient wives, and which was therefore in very lean condition

chichling.definition: A leguminous plant (Lathyrus sativus), with broad flattened seeds which are sometimes used for food

chick.definition: To sprout, as seed in the ground; to vegetate
A child or young person; -- a term of endearment
a young woman; -- often considered offensive

chick flick.definition: A sentimental motion picture that appeals particularly to women.   See flick, n., movie

chick-pea.definition: A Small leguminous plant (Cicer arietinum) of Asia, Africa, and the south of Europe; the chich; the dwarf pea; the gram
Its nutritious seed, used in cookery, and especially, when roasted (parched pulse), as food for travelers in the Eastern deserts

chickabiddy.definition: A chicken; a fowl; also, a trivial term of endearment for a child

chickadee.definition: A small bird, the blackcap titmouse (Parus atricapillus), of North America; -- named from its note

chickaree.definition: The American red squirrel (Tamiasciurus Hudsonius, formerly Sciurus Hudsonius); -- so called from its cry

chickasaws.definition: A tribe of North American Indians (Southern Appalachian) allied to the Choctaws. They formerly occupied the northern part of Alabama and Mississippi, but now live in the Indian Territory

chicken.definition: A young bird or fowl, esp. a young barnyard fowl
A young person; a child; esp. a young woman; a maiden; same as spring chicken

chicken pox.definition: A mild, eruptive disease, generally attacking children only; varicella

chicken-breasted.definition: Having a narrow, projecting chest, caused by forward curvature of the vertebral column

chickenshit.definition: a false statement that is considered to indicate timidity or fear

chickeree.definition: the far western U.S. counterpart of the red squirrel

chickweed.definition: The name of several caryophyllaceous weeds, especially Stellaria media, the seeds and flower buds of which are a favorite food of small birds

chicky.definition: A chicken; -- used as a diminutive or pet name, especially in calling fowls

chicle.definition: A gumlike substance obtained from the bully tree (Mimusops globosa) and sometimes also from the naseberry or sapodilla (Sapota zapotilla). It is more plastic than caoutchouc and more elastic than gutta-percha, as an adulterant of which it is used in England. It is used largely in the United States in making chewing gum

chico.definition: The common greasewood of the western United States (Sarcobatus vermiculatus)
In the Philippines, the  sapodilla or its fruit; also, the marmalade tree or its fruit

chicory.definition: A branching perennial plant (Cichorium Intybus) with bright blue flowers, growing wild in Europe, Asia, and America; also cultivated for its roots and as a salad plant; succory; wild endive. See Endive
The root, which is roasted for mixing with coffee

chicot.definition: a handsome tree of central and eastern North America (Gymnocladus dioica) having large bipinnate leaves and green-white flowers followed by large woody brown pods whose seeds are used as a coffee substitute

chide.definition: To rebuke; to reprove; to scold; to find fault with
Fig.: To be noisy about; to chafe against
To utter words of disapprobation and displeasure; to find fault; to contend angrily
To make a clamorous noise; to chafe

chidingly.definition: In a chiding or reproving manner

chief.definition: The head or leader of any body of men; a commander, as of an army; a head man, as of a tribe, clan, or family; a person in authority who directs the work of others; the principal actor or agent
The principal part; the most valuable portion
The upper third part of the field. It is supposed to be composed of the dexter, sinister, and middle chiefs
Highest in office or rank; principal; head
Principal or most eminent in any quality or action; most distinguished; having most influence; taking the lead; most important; as, the chief topic of conversation; the chief interest of man

chief baron.definition: The presiding judge of the court of exchequer

chief hare.definition: A small rodent (Lagamys princeps) inhabiting the summits of the Rocky Mountains; -- also called crying hare, calling hare, cony, American pika, and little chief hare

chief justice.definition: The presiding justice, or principal judge, of a court

chiefage.definition: A tribute by the head; a capitation tax

chiefly.definition: In the first place; principally; preëminently; above; especially

chiefrie.definition: A small rent paid to the lord paramount

chieftain.definition: A captain, leader, or commander; a chief; the head of a troop, army, or clan

chieftaincy.definition: The rank, dignity, or office of a chieftain

chievance.definition: An unlawful bargain; traffic in which money is exported as discount

chiff-chaff.definition: A species of European warbler (Sylvia hippolais); -- called also chip-chap, and pettychaps

chiffon.definition: Any merely ornamental adjunct of a woman's dress, as a bunch of ribbon, lace, etc
A kind of soft gauzy material used for ruches, trimmings, etc

chiffonier.definition: One who gathers rags and odds and ends; a ragpicker
A receptacle for rags or shreds
A movable and ornamental closet or piece of furniture with shelves or drawers

chigger.definition: a small tropical flea (Tunga penetrans, formerly Pulex penetrans); same as chigoe
a larval mite of the family Trombiculidae that sucks the blood of vertebrates including human beings, causing intense irritation, and serving to transmit several infectious diseases

chiggerflower.definition: an erect perennial of eastern and southern U. S. (Asclepias tuberosa) having showy orange flowers

chignon.definition: A knot, boss, or mass of hair, natural or artificial, worn by a woman at the back of the head

chigoe.definition: A species of flea (Tunga penetrans, formerly Pulex penetrans), common in the West Indies and South America, which often attacks the feet or any exposed part of the human body, and burrowing beneath the skin produces great irritation. When the female is allowed to remain and breed, troublesome sores result, which are sometimes dangerous. See Jigger

chih fu.definition: An official administering a prefecture of China; a prefect, supervising the civil business of the hsiens or districts comprised in his fu (which see)

chih hsien.definition: An official having charge of a hsien, or administrative district, in China; a district magistrate, responsible for good order in his hsien (which see), and having jurisdiction in its civil and criminal cases

chih tai.definition: A Chinese governor general; a tsung tu (which see)

chihuahua.definition: An old breed of tiny short-coated dogs with protruding eyes, originating in Mexico, believed to antedate Aztec civilization

chikara.definition: The goat antelope (Tragops Bennettii) of India

chilblain.definition: A blain, sore, or inflammatory swelling of the feet or hands, produced by exposure to cold, and attended by itching, pain, and sometimes ulceration

child.definition: A son or a daughter; a male or female descendant, in the first degree; the immediate progeny of human parents; -- in law, legitimate offspring. Used also of animals and plants
A descendant, however remote; -- used esp. in the plural; as, the children of Israel; the children of Edom

One who, by character of practice, shows signs of relationship to, or of the influence of, another; one closely connected with a place, occupation, character, etc.; as, a child of God; a child of the devil; a child of disobedience; a child of toil; a child of the people
A young person of either sex. esp. one between infancy and youth; hence, one who exhibits the characteristics of a very young person, as innocence, obedience, trustfulness, limited understanding, etc
To give birth; to produce young

child study.definition: A scientific study of children, undertaken for the purpose of discovering the laws of development of the body and the mind from birth to manhood

childbearing.definition: The act of producing or bringing forth children; parturition

childbed.definition: The state of a woman bringing forth a child, or being in labor; parturition

childbirth.definition: The act of bringing forth a child; travail; labor

childcrowing.definition: The crowing noise made by children affected with spasm of the laryngeal muscles; false croup

childe.definition: A cognomen formerly prefixed to his name by the oldest son, until he succeeded to his ancestral titles, or was knighted; as, Childe Roland

childermas day.definition: A day (December 28) observed by mass or festival in commemoration of the children slain by Herod at Bethlehem; -- called also Holy Innocent's Day

childhood.definition: The state of being a child; the time in which persons are children; the condition or time from infancy to puberty

childish.definition: Of, pertaining to, befitting, or resembling, a child

childishly.definition: In the manner of a child; in a trifling way; in a weak or foolish manner

childishness.definition: The state or quality of being childish; simplicity; harmlessness; weakness of intellect

childlike.definition: Resembling a child, or that which belongs to children; becoming a child; meek; submissive; dutiful

childly.definition: Having the character of a child; belonging, or appropriate, to a child

childness.definition: The manner characteristic of a child

childship.definition: The state or relation of being a child

chilean.definition: of, pertaining to, or characteristic of Chile or its inhabitants; as, Chilean volcanoes
A native or resident of Chile; Chilian

chili.definition: A kind of red pepper. See Capsicum

chiliad.definition: A thousand; the aggregate of a thousand things; especially, a period of a thousand years

chiliagon.definition: A plane figure of a thousand angles and sides

chiliahedron.definition: A figure bounded by a thousand plane surfaces

chilian.definition: The commander or chief of a thousand men

chiliarchy.definition: A body consisting of a thousand men

chiliasm.definition: The doctrine of the personal reign of Christ on earth during the millennium

chiliast.definition: One who believes in the second coming of Christ to reign on earth a thousand years; a millenarian

chill.definition: A moderate but disagreeable degree of cold; a disagreeable sensation of coolness, accompanied with shivering
